    {
        "id": 2554759,
        "project_id": 1663,
        "action_name": "commented on",
        "target_id": 2302313,
        "target_iid": 2302313,
        "target_type": "Note",
        "author_id": 64781,
        "target_title": "Documention: GNOME Wallpaper List XML Format Specification (\u201cgnome-wp-list.dtd\u201d)",
        "created_at": "2024-12-22T06:04:12.023Z",
        "note": {
            "id": 2302313,
            "type": null,
            "body": "Hello, I couldn't find `gnome-wp-list.dtd` in either [`gnome-control-center`](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center) or this repo, so I tried to replicate it from the code. I also couldn't find a specification for wallpapers, only this mention in the [draft for Desktop Themes Specification](https://www.freedesktop.org/wiki/DesktopThemeSpec/):\n\n>Wallpapers should be installed in `$XDG_DATA_DIRS/wallpapers`\n\nThat said, it seems that the wallpaper list XML file is only relevant to gnome-control-center, and not gnome-desktop, so the issue should be moved there.\n\n----\n\nA `.xml` file that is picked up by the Settings app, which is stored in `$XDG_DATA_DIRS/gnome-background-properties`. This file may have some metadata, such as author name, email and license, as seen in the [default Fedora wallpapers](https://gitlab.com/fedora/design/team/backgrounds/workstation-gnome/-/blob/main/backgrounds/montclair.xml.in).\n\nThe tag `name` [seems to be required](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center/-/blob/main/panels/background/cc-background-xml.c?ref_type=heads#L577), works as an [ID](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center/-/blob/main/panels/background/cc-background-xml.c?ref_type=heads#L311-314), and can appear multiple times (to have user friendly names in [different languages](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center/-/blob/main/panels/background/cc-background-xml.c?ref_type=heads#L229-252)).\n\nFrom what I could read, some tags have counterparts in the settings, and they are translated to their actual names in the code.\n\n| Tag in the `.xml` file | Setting in `org.gnome.desktop.background` |\n| ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |\n| `<pcolor>`        | `primary-color`                                |\n| `<scolor>`        | `secondary-color`                              |\n| `<filename>`      | `picture-uri` (`file:` prefix is added)        |\n| `<filename-dark>` | `picture-uri-dark` (`file:` prefix is added)   |\n| `<shade_type>`    | `color-shading-type`                           |\n| `<options>`       | `picture-options`                              |\n\nSome questions that remain:\n\n- Is the tag `filename` required in the `.xml` file? Since the user can use the other settings to set a solid color or gradient background (see below), then the filename could be more or less useless.\n- Is the tag `name` required in the `.xml` file? Maybe it was displayed in the settings app in older versions, but I couldn't find how to access it from the GUI.\n- What is the purpose of `source_url` tag? It mentions [Flickr in the source code](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-control-center/-/blob/main/panels/background/cc-background-item.c?ref_type=heads#L56), but I don't see a counterpart in gnome-desktop.\n\nBased on this information, I wrote the `.dtd` file as well as a `.xsd` one.\n\n[gnome-wp-list.dtd](/uploads/2ecaa06273b161f5df52f2b216237d21/gnome-wp-list.dtd)\n\n[gnome-wp-list.xsd](/uploads/0ea9e1de765e7cfa8d75f90bc1eb5223/gnome-wp-list.xsd)\n\n## The wallpaper file specified in `<filename>` and `<filename-dark>`\n\nFrom what I've read, [gnome-gb.c](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-desktop/-/blob/master/libgnome-desktop/gnome-bg.c?ref_type=heads) is for GTK3 and [gnome-gb/gnome-bg.c](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-desktop/-/blob/master/libgnome-desktop/gnome-bg/gnome-bg.c?ref_type=heads) is for GTK4, but I directly tested the settings to check when the slideshow file is actually used.\n\nCases in which the `picture-uri[-dark]` setting is not used (`picture-options` is set to `none`):\n\n- A solid color background can be generated by setting `color-shading-type` to `solid` and `primary-color` to a valid color\n- A gradient background by setting `color-shading-type` to `horizontal` or `vertical` and setting both `primary-color` and `secondary-color` to valid colors.\n\nCases in which the `picture-uri[-dark]` setting is used (`picture-options` is set to one of the other values):\n\n- If `picture-uri[-dark]` is an image file, then it will directly used (or its first frame in the case of gif/webp animated files).\n- If `picture-uri[-dark]` is a XML file specifying a slideshow, then it will be validated and used.\n\nFrom the code in [gnome-bg/gnome-bg-slide-show.c](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-desktop/-/blob/master/libgnome-desktop/gnome-bg/gnome-bg-slide-show.c?ref_type=heads#L366-444), it seems that the slideshow doesn't have an official spec since it is parsed using GMarkup. Still, I tried to write a `.dtd` file as well as a `.xsd` one, but the `.xsd` can not replicate the full behavior of sized files (either text content or multiple tags):\n\n[gnome-wp.dtd](/uploads/b7ad6174340c23b10a560d40a7029a10/gnome-wp.dtd)\n\n[gnome-wp.xsd](/uploads/886a3c7fef9f0493e9d029515395de28/gnome-wp.xsd)",
